{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:06:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:06:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1597"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1597"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.1,0.08,0.37,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1597"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23741"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after waking with right-sided chest pain. He has always been healthy and has no significant previous medical issues. He is complaining of chest pain and shortness of breath. His blood pressure is 100/65mmHg, pulse rate 100/min, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on room air and temperature 37.1C. An X-ray has been taken (image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation and outpatient review","Admit and observe","Needle aspiration and outpatient review","Intercostal drain insertion","Admit and needle aspiration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a right-sided pneumothorax, with at least 50% of his lung collapsed. Even if he was symptom-free, the guidelines issued by the American College of Chest Physicians recommend admission to hospital and placement of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eunderwater-seal drain\u003C/strong\u003E. In recent years there has been a move towards a more conservative approach, with the management based on the presence of symptoms. These guidelines are for any pneumothorax larger than 20% of the hemithorax, and in one of the size shown in this chest X-ray, a safe approach is drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis symptoms are also worrying and has signs of clinical instability (tachycardia, tachypnoea, chest pain, and breathlessness) warrants intervention with intercostal drainage with underwater seal. In otherwords,\u003Cstrong\u003E observation\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient. Likewise, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eneedle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to allow adequate evacuation of air to reduce the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Be aware of the move towards more conservative management of large pneumothoraces."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. eTG Pneumothorax. Primary spontaneous pneumothorax: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2020. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=pneumothorax\u0026guidelineName=Respiratory\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e91","Brown SG, Ball EL, Perrin K, Asha SE, Braithwaite I, Egerton-Warburton D, et al. Conservative versus interventional treatment for spontaneous pneumothorax. NEJM. 2020 Jan 30;382(5):405-415."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{